				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re:  Charm kiting XP (which method is best)<a name="69070"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Nov 5 04 2:45 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">We cant agree at what break point the dmg done by pet and by the bard determines XP penalties.</span></blockquote>
<br />
The pet XP penalties (summoned and charmed) have been changed multiple times over the last few years so it's common for people to disagree on this point. Often people will hear about how it works, then leave the game for a while or not keep up with patch messages, and thus are unaware that there was a new change afterward.
<br />

<br />
To the best of my knowledge, this is how things work currently (use at your own risk):
<br />

<br />
SUMMONED and CHARMED pets:
<br />
If the pet does ALL the damage to the target, it takes 75% of the XP.
<br />

<br />
SUMMONED pets only:
<br />
If you do at least 1 point of damage to the target, a summoned pet will not take any XP.
<br />

<br />
CHARMED pets only (regular charm, not Dire Charm):
<br />
If you do at least 1 point of damage to the target, a charmed pet will take up to 33% of the XP, scaled based on how much damage it does:
<br />
99.999% of damage - 33% XP
<br />
50% of damage - 16.5% XP
<br />
10% of damage - 3.3% XP
<br />
etc.
<br />

<br />
This current XP penalty system is independent of grouping, that is, it works the same regardless of whether or not the pet's owner is in a group.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
